Anonymous Thu 03 Feb 2022 05:34:07 No.45253080 Report
Quoted By: >>45261460
>>45252568
I find it funny that I've told people exactly this.
It's doubly funny that when Jordan was going on about dresses (the way Tolkein did for trees or songs, to boot), his minor characters stuck with me far more than other contemporary epic fantasy.
On the other hand, Asimov pared things down so far that at times the story became one-dimensional. If you're not already familiar with the pulpy pacing some of his earlier stuff had, his shorter material isn't for you. The characters that stuck with me were the ones that had a world to act against; the Elijah Baileys, Seldons, and the Mules.
Like worldbuilding, you can focus too much on the characters and the big picture suffers. Find a good balance and learn to dial it a bit to either side for pacing.

Anonymous Thu 03 Feb 2022 10:56:23 No.45256791 Report
Quoted By: >>45256993 >>45258530 >>45259085
>>45255081
>doors usually open inwards
No. Not in the U.S. or most of the world. By law, for safety reasons, external doors to buildings, especially buildings accessed by the public and by workplace staff, MUST open outward.

In the 1930s (or, maybe earlier, could go back to ~1900 or so) there was a very infamous fire in a factory where the doors opened inward. When people were attempting to escape, the doors got forced shut by the crowd. As the people at the back of the crowd pushed toward the doors, there was no way to open them due to all the bodies being crushed against them. This happened more than once, in a movie theater also, but the one with the factory was insane, something like hundreds dead, all packed into crushed meat that was then roasted alive. Took days to cut into the building and clean the exits.

Laws were passed to prevent that from ever happening again. It's also why all exits on public buildings have to have crash bars to let people escape in an emergency. glass doors that slide sideways are designed for people to push and crash through in an emergency. If you tried to install inward-opening doors on a building today, you'd get shut down by safety & building inspectors until you fixed the problem.

There are probably some extremely rare exceptions (historical building restoration in some cases, for example), backed by extensive paperwork demonstrating why there is no other option, but I doubt it's more than about one in every ten thousand doors that open outward.

> t. Hi, I worked in industrial construction for half a decade. It's baked into the building codes.

Older science fiction (before the mid 80's) tended far more towards world-focused storytelling as oppose to the character-focused storytelling that's held up as the Holy Grail in writing circles today. You don't even need to stick to Asimov to see it, though I suppose Asimov is a rather extreme example of it. But for all the praise Philip K. Dick gets for portraying crazy, tumble-down realities he was never a character-focused writer. Most of his characters are simple, and Ursula k. LeGuin pointed out most of his female characters are bitches. But LeGuin is overrated, so what does she know?

But the world-focused storytelling of older science fiction makes for some great snappy, imaginative storytelling. It all comes down to taste, but I've always appreciated Big Idea stories. And it's not like everyone who tries character-focused writing is actually good at it, and the modern focus on it seems to approach narcissism at some points.
